The government has given companies up to five years to bring their operations into compliance with a strict new environmental law approved earlier this year, a newspaper reported Saturday.
It is estimated that 80 % of logging in Brazil is illegal.
And many of the country's national parks are known as ``paper parks'' because there is nothing to prevent them from being overrun.
Even Brazil's announcement with the World Bank and World Wildlife Fund that 62 million acres will be set aside has been met with some skepticism since preserving the land may be difficult.
